		</hint>
		<answer>
			<ol marker="a.">
		      <li>
		          <table xml:id="T-8a-2-act-2-log-ans">
		            <title>Finding the derivatives of <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> at <m>a = 1</m>.</title>
		              <tabular top="none" bottom="none">
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x) =</m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>\ln(x)</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(1) =</m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>0</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>x^{-1}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>1</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>-1 \cdot x^{-2}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-2)(-1)x^{-3}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-2)(-1)</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-3)(-2)(-1)x^{-4}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-3)(-2)(-1)</m></cell>
		                </row>
		              </tabular>
		            </table>		
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		<m>
                			T_4(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4
                		</m>.
                	</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		      <figure xml:id="F-8a-2-act-2-ans">
							    <caption>The function <m>f(x)=\ln(x)</m> and its degree <m>1</m> Taylor approximation  <m>T_1(x) = x-1</m> near the point <m>(1,f(1))</m>.</caption>
							      <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_act_2_soln" />
							  </figure>
						<m>T_4(x)</m> provides a much more accurate approximation of <m>f(x)</m> than <m>T_1(x)</m>.	
                	</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		 <m>|f(x) - T_4(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>0.29 \lt x \lt 1.97</m>.
                	</p>
                </li>		
                <li>
                	<p>
                		<m>T_5(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4 + \frac{1}{5}(x-1)^5</m>; <m>T_6(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4 + \frac{1}{5}(x-1)^5 - \frac{1}{6}(x-1)^6</m>.  
                	</p>		

                	<p>	
                		<m>|f(x) - T_5(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.24 \lt x \lt 1.999</m>;  <m>|f(x) - T_6(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.21 \lt x \lt 2</m>.  While the interval of accuracy gets wider as the degree increases, it seems not to extend past <m>x = 2</m> and doesn't move much to the left.  
                	</p>
                </li>    
			</ol>			
		</answer>
		<solution>

		<p>
			 Let <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> and consider the degree <m>4</m> Taylor polynomial approximation 
			 <me>
			 	T_4(x) = c_0 + c_1 (x-1) + c_2 (x-1)^2 + c_3(x-1)^3 + c_4(x-1)^4
			 </me>.
		</p>

			<ol marker="a.">
		      <li>
		          <table xml:id="T-8a-2-act-2-log-soln">
		            <title>Finding the derivatives of <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> at <m>a = 1</m>.</title>
		              <tabular top="none" bottom="none">
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x) =</m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>\ln(x)</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(1) =</m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>0</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>x^{-1}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>1</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>-1 \cdot x^{-2}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-2)(-1)x^{-3}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'''(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-2)(-1)</m></cell>
		                </row>
		                <row>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(x) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-3)(-2)(-1)x^{-4}</m></cell>
		                  <cell halign="right"><m>f^{(4)}(1) = </m></cell>
		                  <cell><m>(-3)(-2)(-1)</m></cell>
		                </row>
		              </tabular>
		            </table>		
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		From our work in (a) and the fact that <m>c_k = \frac{f^{(k)}(a)}{k!}</m>, we have 
                		<me>
                			T_4(x) = 0 + 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{(-2)(-1)}{3!}(x-1)^3 + \frac{(-3)(-2)(-1)}{4!}(x-1)^4
                		</me>,
                		so that
                		<me>
                			T_4(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4
                		</me>.
                	</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		Plotting <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m>, <m>T_1(x) = x - 1</m>, and <m>T_4(x)</m> to the figure,
                		      <figure xml:id="F-8a-2-act-2-soln">
							    <caption>The function <m>f(x)=\ln(x)</m> and its degree <m>1</m> Taylor approximation  <m>T_1(x) = x-1</m> near the point <m>(1,f(1))</m>.</caption>
							      <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_act_2_soln" />
							  </figure>
						we notice that <m>T_4(x)</m> provides a much more accurate approximation of <m>f(x)</m> than <m>T_1(x)</m>.	
                	</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                	<p>
                		 Using a slider in Desmos to experiment, <m>|f(x) - T_4(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>0.29 \lt x \lt 1.97</m>.
                	</p>
                </li>		
                <li>
                	<p>
                		Following the pattern in <xref ref="T-8a-2-act-2-log-soln">Table</xref>, we expect <m>T_5(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4 + \frac{1}{5}(x-1)^5</m> and <m>T_6(x) = 1 (x-1) - \frac{1}{2} (x-1)^2 + \frac{1}{3}(x-1)^3 - \frac{1}{4}(x-1)^4 + \frac{1}{5}(x-1)^5 - \frac{1}{6}(x-1)^6</m>.  
                	</p>		

                	<p>	
                		Further computations show that <m>|f(x) - T_5(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.24 \lt x \lt 1.999</m>, and  <m>|f(x) - T_6(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for about <m>0.21 \lt x \lt 2</m>.  While the interval of accuracy gets wider as the degree increases, it seems not to extend past <m>x = 2</m> and doesn't move much to the left.  This is different from how we observed the interval of accuracy continue to get wider and wider without bound for <m>f(x) = \cos(x)</m> as we increased the degree of approximation in <xref ref="act-8a-2-1">Activity</xref>.
                	</p>
                </li>    
			</ol>
			
		</solution>
